28/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd0%2Fcc%2F5f1f000245e39eca64259dc04ed2%2Fstillbirth-diptych-1-4.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2700x1519+0+128/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd0%2Fcc%2F5f1f000245e39eca64259dc04ed2%2Fstillbirth-diptych-1-4.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2700x1519+0+128/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd0%2Fcc%2F5f1f000245e39eca64259dc04ed2%2Fstillbirth-diptych-1-4.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2700x1519+0+128/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd0%2Fcc%2F5f1f000245e39eca64259dc04ed2%2Fstillbirth-diptych-1-4.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2700x1519+0+128/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd0%2Fcc%2F5f1f000245e39eca64259dc04ed2%2Fstillbirth-diptych-1-4.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2700x1519+0+128/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd0%2Fcc%2F5f1f000245e39eca64259dc04ed2%2Fstillbirth-diptych-1-4.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2700x1519+0+128/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fd0%2Fcc%2F5f1f000245e39eca64259dc04ed2%2Fstillbirth-diptych-1-4.jpg" class="img" alt="Clockwise, from top left: Laura Forer, Michelle Alette, Domenique Rice, Jen Loga, Dr. Patty Ng and Marise Angibeau-Gray" loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Clockwise, from top left: Laura Forer, Michelle Alette, Domenique Rice, Jen Loga, Dr. Patty Ng and Marise Angibeau-Gray                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Nancy Borowick                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Nancy Borowick found that photography was therapeutic for her after she lost both of her parents&lt;/strong&gt; within 364 days of one another. It continued to have healing power when she found herself deep in depression 13 months after the traumatic birth of her son. Borowick turned to social media to ask others about their experiences with birth trauma. One grandmother asked her, "Are you looking for stories about stillbirth?" The question prompted her to start The Loss Mother's Stone, a project she hopes will draw awareness to women's stories, educate Americans and destigmatize the conversation between doctors and patients. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;📷 &lt;strong&gt;See photos and videos&lt;/strong&gt; from mothers &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/the-picture-show/2024/12/09/g-s1-5058/mothers-share-grief-from-stillbirth"&gt;sharing their grief in this project&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-37698" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 7282;         --source-height: 4096;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/7282x4096+0+241/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F24%2F73%2F4b8494d543cc94e5c3f2c0932a0a%2Fajones.jpg" class="img" alt="After The Onion was named the winning bidder for Alex Jones&amp;#039; assets at a bankruptcy auction last month, the losing bidder tried to stop the sale, saying the process was rigged and “fatally flawed.”" loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 After The Onion was named the winning bidder for Alex Jones' assets at a bankruptcy auction last month, the losing bidder tried to stop the sale, saying the process was rigged and "fatally flawed."                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Joe Buglewicz/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ol class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A bankruptcy judge has rejected a bid by The Onion's owners &lt;/strong&gt;to buy Alex Jones' Infowars, saying the &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/10/nx-s1-5224170/infowars-alex-jones-the-onion-bankruptcy-judge"&gt;offer and process were flawed&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;New Jersey Gov. Phil Murphy signed a new law Monday that limits&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href="https://whyy.org/articles/new-jersey-book-banning-schools-libraries/"&gt;how a book can be banned&lt;/a&gt; in schools and public libraries and protects librarians from lawsuits. (via &lt;a href="https://whyy.org/"&gt;WHYY&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The U.S.' first state-sanctioned facility for people to use illegal drugs under medical supervision&lt;/strong&gt; opened yesterday in Rhode Island. The facilities are part of an &lt;a href="https://thepublicsradio.org/health/rhode-island-opens-first-state-sanctioned-overdose-prevention-center-in-the-nation/"&gt;effort to prevent overdoses&lt;/a&gt;. (via &lt;a href="https://thepublicsradio.org/"&gt;The Public's Radio&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This newsletter was edited by &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/people/859721331/suzanne-nuyen"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Suzanne Nuyen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
